instances of the same INC service to maximize resource sharing benefits and keep the set of active INC services (per switch) small, (3) informed flavor selection where the scheduler always tries to select the Å‚cheapestÅ¾ flavor with respect to the task counts in task groups and the aggregate flavor costs of tasks in all the task groups belonging to the flavor, and (4) locality-aware scheduling of tasks on machines close to (or covered by the same network topology tree) the running tasks of the same or directly connected task groups.
HIRE uses a multi-dimensional cost vector ğœÃ¬ for each edge in the flow network. We further transform ğœÃ¬ to a scalar cost value ğœ, so that HIRE can run the min-cost max-flow (MCMF) problem. To this end, we flatten ğœÃ¬ by applying a weighted sum. The weights can be used to model priorities or other custom policies. Tab. 4 summarizes all cost terms of ğœÃ¬, and refers to sub-cost functions Î¦ specified below.
Job-independent costs. The first two edge types in Tab. 4, i.e., Mğ‘  /Mğ‘› â†’ K, are job-independent and evaluate machine resource utilization and balance. Costs are lower for machines with lower utilization, and with higher variation among the load of all resources dimensions. Furthermore, Mğ‘› â†’ K considers the network level in the topology and the number of different active INC services, so that it is less attractive to choose a switch for INC that is not close to a server or which combines more different INC services on the same Mğ‘›. More specifically, we define two cost functions:

Î¦âŒŠPâŒ‹ Å› A cost term proportional to the number of active INC services on an Mğ‘›, normalized to the maximum number of INC services that could run on a particular Mğ‘›.
Î¦ToR Å› A cost term inversely proportional to the number of network hops an Mğ‘› node is away from its closest Mğ‘  node, normalized to the largest possible distance.
Job-dependent cost. The remaining columns of Tab. 4 are jobdependent edge costs. The first two rows (utilization and multiplexing) define cost terms so that HIRE prefers allocations for which the resource demand matches better the available resources. More specifically, the cost is smaller if the task group uses a similar portion, with respect to current load, in each resource dimension. Furthermore, we define the following cost functions for locality, resource interference, and priority. The high-level goal of these cost functions is to co-locate tasks (Î¦loc), leverage INC resource sharing (Î¦new), and prioritize long waiting task groups (Î¦delay).
Î¦loc Å› For server tasks, HIRE prefers subtrees which already host tasks of the same or a directly connected task group of the same polymorphic resource request (PolyReq). For INC tasks, HIRE prefers switches that are close (in terms of network hops) to other switches involved in the same or connected task group. We combine the two locality preferences so that switches consider servers and vice versa, simply by checking both flow network parts (server and shadow) for the same node in the topology for calculating the cost term. More specifically, we define two locality metrics, Î¥ (Eq. 6) for the server part of flow network (with Mğ‘  and Nğ‘  ), and Î“ (Alg. 1) for the INC shadow network (with Mğ‘› and Nğ‘›). HIRE takes the weighted average (using task counts) of Î¥ and Î“ and normalizes the value afterwards. There are three cases to consider: (a) For G â†’ N, Î¦loc checks the two nodes Nğ‘›, Nğ‘  that correspond to the same location in the data center (DC), and returns the combination of norm(Î“ğ‘ ğ‘›,ğº ) and Î¥ğ‘ ğ‘ ,ğº , respectively. (b) For G â†’ Mğ‘›, Î¦loc simply considers the corresponding Nğ‘› to calculate the costs as per (a). (c) For G â†’ Mğ‘  , Î¦loc considers a simplified version of Eq. 6 to evaluate the number of tasks running on M, but considers Î“ and Î¥ of the parent Nğ‘  for the connected

